ations, family and cultural influences&quot;.   Neither of us i=\r\ns at the liberal/casual extreme nor the very rigid traditional extreme. Bot=\r\nh of us seem to be somewhere in the middle though at different points.   \n =\r\n \n\n&gt;&gt;&gt; &gt;If one reaches samadhi directly when Kundalini awakens, things &gt;&gt;&gt;a=\r\nre fine. But, that may not &gt;&gt;happen. &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;Kundalini can take many different =\r\npaths and go to different places. Depending on the &gt;&gt;&gt;impurities in various=\r\n nadis, various experiences are possible. If a sadhaka is unprepared to han=\r\ndle &gt;&gt;&gt;the experience, it can create &gt;&gt;&gt;problems. One can experience someth=\r\ning nice and become proud and &gt;&gt;&gt;egoistic and get stuck there. One can expe=\r\nrience a very fierce form of divine and get scared to death &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;or go mad. =\r\nMany &gt;&gt;&gt;possibilities are there.&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n\n\nExcellent point. Here I will share s=\r\nomething from my own experience to illustrate this. Initially I was hesitan=\r\nt to write about it, but decided to go ahead as it might help put things in=\r\n a better perspective. During 1989-1992, I pursued sadhana single-mindedly =\r\nas a brahmachari, having given up other secular studies. Those days I used =\r\nto live mostly in the company of brahmacharis and sanyasis. Some of my co-s=\r\nadhakas of those days went on to become fully ordained monks later. Swadhya=\r\nya, yogabhyasa and occasional tirthayatras formed the mainstay of my sadhan=\r\na at this time. Somewhere towards the second half of this period I started =\r\ndoing Devi Mahatmya parayana on my own without any initiation. Things were =\r\nfine and I made some progress probably owing to a combination of many facto=\r\nrs. After spending three years in spiritual studies and sadhana, I decided =\r\nto return home and pursue medical studies in accordance with my mother&#39;s wi=\r\nsh. However I continued with my sadhana whilst pursuing my medical studies =\r\ntoo.\n\nAround early 95, I started doing Devi Mahatmya parayana with *more* v=\r\nigour. Within a month I started having piercing headaches, my body would be=\r\n quite hot to touch and my blood pressure would shoot up to around 150/110 =\r\non and off. After conducting the standard investigations, Dr. Rao from the =\r\nDept of Medicine, who had already taken a liking to me, suspected that it *=\r\nmight* have something to do with my sadhanas too. Things continued to be th=\r\ne same for some more months, till I got introduced to Swami Sachchidananda =\r\nin what seemed to be a chance meeting. During the course of conversation Sw=\r\namiji asked me to meet him alone the next day after coming to know about my=\r\n practice of the Devi mahatmya parayana. After interacting everyday for a w=\r\neek Swamiji initiated me properly into Sri Sri Chandi path.  After a week o=\r\nr so after the initiation all the symptoms subsided. The blood pressure, jw=\r\nara and headaches, all normalized. It has been around 15 years since then a=\r\nnd none of the symptoms have recurred. What&#39;s more, I had some very powerfu=\r\nl internal experiences in quick succession during the following week itself=\r\n after initiation. This is my experience.\n                                 =\r\n\n\n&gt;&gt;&gt;(6) If one is not looking for any specific results and doing a &gt;&gt;&gt;mant=\r\nra just for spiritual progress with a &gt;&gt;&gt;sense of surrender, one is safe.&gt;&gt;=\r\n&gt;&gt;\n\n\nRight from the start whatever sadhanas I did, were all done largely as=\r\n a spiritual pursuit only with no specific results in mind at least conscio=\r\nusly. However the general desire to make progress would have naturally been=\r\n there.\n\n\n&gt;&gt;&gt; (5) Especially if one does not engage in raja yoga/hatha yoga=\r\n &gt;&gt;&gt;practices that are meant to forcefully &gt;&gt;&gt;awaken and raise Kundalini &gt;&gt;=\r\n&gt;and if one does not consciously think in terms of &gt;&gt;&gt;raising Kundalini, on=\r\ne is &gt;&gt;&gt;safe.&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n\n\nThough I was not consciously thinking of raising Kundal=\r\nni or anything like that and was just focusing on sadhana, you are right ab=\r\nout the raja yoga/hatha yoga practices. Yogabhyasa was a regular part of my=\r\n sadhana during 89-92. In fact I became a qualified Yogacharya during this =\r\ntime. However Devi Mahatmya parayana was part of my sadhana along with yoga=\r\nbhyasa since early 91-92 during which time things were fine. It was only in=\r\n 94 that I resumed Devi Mahatmya parayana more seriously. Of course I was d=\r\noing my yogabhyasa too at this time. I have already written about the rest.=\r\n  \n\nMy stance regarding the role of initiation stems from my own experience=\r\n as well as the instructions coming down through the guru parampara. Howeve=\r\nr I can appreciate your stance as well. Let me add something more here. No =\r\ntwo individuals have the same experience in such matters. Some may experien=\r\nce nothing significant after initiation and may still be progressing. Some =\r\nmay need more guidance due to the nature of the specific practices that the=\r\ny have got into. Eitherways She will take care.  \n\n\n\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Given this state=\r\nment, the difference of opinion between us are very subtle.&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n\n\nIt is bet=\r\nter for all of us to focus more on the underlying unity of our thought and =\r\nnot on the difference. Moreover overstretching such discussions can deter s=\r\nome sadhakas which is not something that anyone of us would wish for.\n \n\n &gt;=\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt; One word on guilt here. If someone is doing a practice and feels a sens=\r\ne of guilt, it blocks the &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;practice from working &gt;&gt;&gt;effectively. Please =\r\ndo whatever sadhana you do, without a sense of guilt. If &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;you have the s=\r\nense of guilt, work on overcoming it. If &gt;&gt;&gt;you cannot overcome it, it may =\r\nbe a good &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;idea to find a &gt;&gt;&gt;sadhana with which you feel comfortable and=\r\n have no sense of guilt.&gt;&gt;&gt;\n\n\nI agree that there are many good sadhakas doi=\r\nng Sri Sri Chandipath without initiation. There is no need for anyone to fe=\r\nel guilty. It is only good samskaras and vasanas that attract a sadhaka to =\r\nSri Sri Chandi. One does not need to feel guilty for worshipping or loving =\r\nthe Goddess.  If you take my own example, initially I did the sadhana witho=\r\nut initiation. It is only Her Grace that I was initiated. I didn&#39;t even ask=\r\n for it. If it is meant to be it will be. Things will happen on their own a=\r\nccord in the natural flow. The main thing is that the sadhaka should leave =\r\nthe rest to the compassionate Goddess and trust that She will take care of =\r\neverything.                   \n\nOn this note I suggest that we should wrap =\r\nup the topic of initiation. From my side I wish to say nothing more. \n\nI mi=\r\nght be off the list till another fortnight or so as I am travelling.\n    \n\n=\r\nAll Glories to the Goddess!!!\n\nRegards,\nSatya Prakash   \n\n\n=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=\r\n=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=\r\n=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D\n\n--- In vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com, Narasi=\r\nmha PVR Rao &lt;pvr@...&gt; wrote:\n&gt;\n&gt; Namaste Satya Prakash garu,\n&gt;  \n&gt; Welcome =\r\nto the list and it is a pleasure to have your learned company here.\n&gt;  \n&gt; T=\r\nraditional conventions are not without basis, but I suggest we need to unde=\r\nrstand their motivation.\n&gt;  \n&gt; *        *        *\n&gt;  \n&gt; When one chants lo=\r\nng prayers such as Chandipath, Vishnu sahasra naama stotra, Aditya Hridayam=\r\n etc, it requires a lot of conscious mental activity. One mostly cannot go =\r\ninto samadhi while chanting them (though there can be exceptions). On the o=\r\nther hand, when one chants Gayatri mantra or ashtakshari mantra or dwadasak=\r\nshari mantra or panchakshari mantra or navarna mantra or various beeja mant=\r\nras or other small mantras, it requires a minimal amount of conscious menta=\r\nl activity. With repetitive and minimal mental activity, there is a possibi=\r\nlity of momentary cessation of mental activity and entering samadhi OR awak=\r\nening of Kundalini and progress towards samadhi.\n&gt;  \n&gt; If one reaches samad=\r\nhi directly when Kundalini awakens, things are fine. But, that may not happ=\r\nen. Kundalini can take many different paths and go to different places. Dep=\r\nending on the impurities in various nadis, various experiences are possible=\r\n. If a sadhaka is unprepared to handle the experience, it can create proble=\r\nms. One can experience something nice and become proud and egoistic and get=\r\n stuck there. One can experience a very fierce form of divine and get scare=\r\nd to death or go mad. Many possibilities are there.\n&gt;  \n&gt; Thus, practices t=\r\nhat can truly awaken one were kept limited to the initiated. Guru would ass=\r\ness the progress and readiness of a sadhaka and initiate one when one is re=\r\nady.\n&gt;  \n&gt; *        *        *\n&gt;  \n&gt; However, there are a few things that a=\r\nre different in today&#39;s times:\n&gt;  \n&gt; (1) There are very few people who are =\r\nready to experience something. Most people will just do sadhana, burn some =\r\nbasic blocking karmas and not really experience much. At most, some people =\r\nwill experience an awakening and just a little movement of Kundalini.\n&gt; (2)=\r\n There are very few gurus who are indeed capable of assessing and guiding a=\r\n sadhaka well. Most initiations are a mere formality.\n&gt; (3) With the insist=\r\nence on initiation etc, we may be blocking, in the coming years, the very f=\r\new sadhakas who MAY actually achieve some progress with a mantra, from even=\r\n trying it.\n&gt; (4) If a sadhaka surrenders and has the attitude of &quot;I do not=\r\n know the right way. I am just doing what I am capable of. Please take care=\r\n of me Mother&quot;, none of the risks I mentioned above will really apply.\n&gt; (5=\r\n) Especially if one does not engage in raja yoga/hatha yoga practices that =\r\nare meant to forcefully awaken and raise Kundalini and if one does not cons=\r\nciously think in terms of raising Kundalini, one is safe.\n&gt; (6) If one is n=\r\not looking for any specific results and doing a mantra just for spiritual p=\r\nrogress with a sense of surrender, one is safe.\n&gt;  \n&gt; *        *        *\n&gt;=\r\n  \n&gt; Apart from assessing the readiness, there are some more functions perf=\r\normed by an initiating guru:\n&gt;  \n&gt; (1) A guru can jumpstart one&#39;s sadhana w=\r\nith a mantra and results can come faster.\n&gt;  \n&gt; However, this expects a gur=\r\nu of some caliber and achievement with the mantra. After all, if one wants =\r\na one-on-one audience with Sachin Tendulkar or Roger Federer or Barack Obam=\r\na, being introduced to them by someone they know and someone that had a one=\r\n-on-one audience with them earlier can be helpful (instead of introducing b=\r\ny oneself). If someone who merely read more about them but is not any close=\r\nr to them tries to introduce you to them, will it even get their attention?=\r\n\n&gt;  \n&gt; Now-a-days, most people do not have access to gurus who have experie=\r\nnced the divine with a mantra. Such people are very rare. One&#39;s best bet is=\r\n to do sadhana by oneself, using all the tools given by rishis and various =\r\nspiritual masters. When one is ready (and if it is needed), a guru may come=\r\n and take one&#39;s sadhana to the next level.\n&gt;  \n&gt; (2) A guru can mould the c=\r\norrect attitude in sadhaka before a sadhana is taken up.\n&gt;  \n&gt; However, the=\r\nre are sadhakas initiated in powerful mantras and not having the right atti=\r\ntude. For example, I know people initiated into Bagalamukhi mantra and tryi=\r\nng to use it to win litigation. If one does not know that a &quot;Mahavidya&quot; (su=\r\npreme knowledge) is for overcoming conditioning and realizing self and not =\r\nfor winning court cases, one&#39;s initiation is no good.\n&gt;  \n&gt; On the other ha=\r\nnd, I know some people not formally initiated into Chandipath, but doing Ch=\r\nandi homam daily with saptashati and also navarna mantra. I know that they =\r\ndo not have any specific material goals and are overcoming the few desires =\r\nthat were originally there at the back of the mind. The are making quick pr=\r\nogress spiritually and their thinking is getting transformed nicely. Despit=\r\ne having no formal initiation, aren&#39;t they worshipping Chandi as a Mahavidy=\r\na?\n&gt;  \n&gt; Bottomline is that one can mould one&#39;s own attitude through a form=\r\nal initiation or through reading scriptures, satsanga and constant contempl=\r\nation. One thing may work better in one case and another thing in another c=\r\nase.\n&gt;  \n&gt; (3) A guru can teach the correct procedure of a sadhana.\n&gt;  \n&gt; H=\r\nowever, role of procedural correctness in success is a higher in sadhanas f=\r\nor specific results than sadhana for spiritual progress. I maintain that th=\r\ne art of getting specific results from sadhanas is being hidden more and mo=\r\nre as Kali progresses, for a reason. I suggest that it is useless to even t=\r\nhink in those terms and pursue it.\n&gt;  \n&gt; Mantras like navarna mantra can ju=\r\nst be meditated on, without any specific procedure. When one is ready and p=\r\nure enough, they can give one an experience of the divine. Mantras like Sid=\r\ndha Kunjika stotra, that codify several specific sadhanas to get specific r=\r\nesults, are anyway inaccessible to most people of this age! They are only a=\r\nvailable in codified form and gurus who can decode them will keep disappear=\r\ning more and more.\n&gt;  \n&gt; *        *        *\n&gt;  \n&gt; &gt; For those who are alre=\r\nady doing Sri Sri Chandi path without initiation, there is\n&gt; &gt; no need to w=\r\norry or be confused. ... Please keep doing whatever you are doing.\n&gt;  \n&gt; Gi=\r\nven this statement, the difference of opinion between us are very subtle.\n&gt;=\r\n  \n&gt; One word on guilt here. If someone is doing a practice and feels a sen=\r\nse of guilt, it blocks the practice from working effectively. Please do wha=\r\ntever sadhana you do, without a sense of guilt. If you have the sense of gu=\r\nilt, work on overcoming it. If you cannot overcome it, it may be a good ide=\r\na to find a sadhana with which you feel comfortable and have no sense of gu=\r\nilt.\n&gt;  \n&gt; &gt; Things will happen on their own accord in the natural flow. Le=\r\nave the rest to\n&gt; &gt; the compassionate Goddess.\n&gt;  \n&gt; That&#39;s the bottomline.=\r\n Even if one were initiated, it would be quite difficult to not leave thing=\r\ns to the Goddess and make things happen as one wanted. Start sadhana with s=\r\nome level of surrender. Then, sadhana will help increase the level of surre=\r\nnder. \n&gt;  \n&gt; *        *        *\n&gt;  \n&gt; Nagraj garu,\n&gt;  \n&gt; The opinion refer=\r\nred to in your question 2 is not without basis. But again, we need to under=\r\nstand the motivation to put it in the right perspective.\n&gt;  \n&gt; If one exper=\r\niences divine through sadhana with Gayatri mantra (or any mantra), then it =\r\nis easy for one to experience divine with another mantra. One can just pick=\r\n up a mantra, do it and experience relatively quickly.\n&gt;  \n&gt; However, if on=\r\ne was merely initiated in Gayatri mantra (or any mantra) and did not really=\r\n make much spiritual progress with it, that does not place one in any kind =\r\nof advantage when it comes to sadhana with another mantra. That is my opini=\r\non.\n&gt;  \n&gt; Best regards,\n&gt; Narasimha\n&gt; -------------------------------------=\r\n------------------------------\n&gt;   Free Jyoti